fields.value: The Daily Tar Heel Evaluation, Spring 2005

dsDescriptionValue.value:
The purpose of this survey (Credibility), which was administered in Spring 2005, is to evaluate student trust in the Daily Tar Heel as one measure of the newspaper's quality.

The purpose of this research (Editorial Accuracy) is to evaluate the editorial accuracy of the Daily Tar Heel as a measure of the student newspaper's quality. Analysis focused on copy editing errors contained in the Daily Tar Heel from 2000-2001 school year, the first archive online, to the 2004-2005 school year.

The purpose of this research (Editorial Vigor) is to evaluate the editorial vigor (the extent to which a newspaper's editorials engage the community, challenge the status quo, and encourage readers to take action) of the Daily Tar Heel through a systematic investigation of 80 editorials that ran in the student newspaper between Oct. 18, 2005 and Dec. 7, 2005. Four independent coders were utilized to focus on four independent variables: (1) Is the topic Local? (2) Is the topic controversial? (3) Does the editorial take a position on the topic? And (4) Does the editorial offer actionable information.

The purpose of this research (Readability) is to evaluate the readability of the Daily Tar Heel through a systematic investigation of 400 articles drawn from Oct. 15, 2004 to Jan. 31, 2005.

The purpose of this research (Reporting Accuracy) is to evaluate the reporting accuracy of the Daily Tar Heel through a survey of story sources conducted in Spring 2005.
